2026-06-07 | Create Binary Tree From Descriptions

	Question
Build the binary tree and return the root node.
	Key Insight
We need two things:
1.	Create TreeNode objects for every value.
2.	Find the root.
A root is the only node that never appears as a child.
	Approach
1.	Maintain:
		value → TreeNode*
2.	For every description:
		create parent node if absent
		create child node if absent
3.	Connect parent and child.
4.	Store every child value in a set.
5.	After processing all descriptions:
		the node not present in child set
		is the root.
6.	Return that node.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* createBinaryTree(vector<vector<int>>& descriptions) {
        unordered_map<int, TreeNode*> mp;
        unordered_set<int> children;
        for(auto &d : descriptions) {
            int parent = d[0];
            int child = d[1];
            int isLeft = d[2];
            if(!mp.count(parent))
                mp[parent] = new TreeNode(parent);
            if(!mp.count(child))
                mp[child] = new TreeNode(child);
            if(isLeft)
                mp[parent]->left = mp[child];
            else
                mp[parent]->right = mp[child];
            children.insert(child);
        }
        for(auto &d : descriptions) {
            int parent = d[0];
            if(!children.count(parent))
                return mp[parent];
        }
        return nullptr;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Every node except the root appears exactly once as a child.
So after building all parent-child connections:
		root =
		node that never appears as a child.
This allows us to find the root in O(n) time while constructing the tree.
